<section xml:id="sec-arcs-chords-and-segments" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Arcs, Chords, and Segments</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.2 Angle Properties of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Identify an arc, chord, and segment in a circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    Learners identify and describe arcs, chords, and segments in circles, and distinguish between minor and major arcs.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials Needed</title>
                <p>
                    Paper, compass, ruler, protractor, and a set of coloured pencils or markers.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Guide learners through diagrams and ask questions that focus on identifying parts of a circle and comparing curved and straight boundaries.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            Learners work in groups to study or draw a circle with centre O and points A, B, C and D on the circumference.
            In each group, identify the following in your diagram:
            <ol>
                <li><p>The chord AB</p></li>
                <li><p>The minor arc ACB</p></li>
                <li><p>The major arc ADB</p></li>
                <li><p>The segment defined by chord CD</p></li>
                <li><p>The sector formed by radii OC and OD</p></li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <figure>
            <caption>Circle diagram with chord AB, minor arc ACB, major arc ADB, and sector COD.</caption>
            <image>
                <shortdescription>A circle with labelled points A, B, C, D, and O showing the chord, arcs, and sector.</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2.5);
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (A) at (160:2.5);
                        \coordinate (B) at (20:2.5);
                        \coordinate (C) at (-40:2.5);
                        \coordinate (D) at (120:2.5);
                        \draw[thick] (A) -- (B);
                        \draw[blue, very thick] (A) arc (160:20:2.5);
                        \draw[blue, very thick] (A) arc (160:120:2.5);
                        \draw[red, thick] (O) -- (C);
                        \draw[red, thick] (O) -- (D);
                        \node[above left] at (A) {A};
                        \node[above right] at (B) {B};
                        \node[below right] at (C) {C};
                        \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                        \node[below] at (O) {O};
                        \node[below right] at (1.1,-0.3) {ACB};
                        \node[left] at (-1.7,0.3) {ADB};
                        \node[near end, above] at (0.2,-0.1) {OC};
                        \node[near end, left] at (-0.25,0.9) {OD};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <p>
            Understanding arcs, chords, and segments strengthens learners' ability to read circle diagrams and prepares them for reasoning about angles and lengths in later lessons.
        </p>
        <p>
            The key idea is that an arc is a curved part of the circle, a chord is a straight line joining two points on the circle, and a segment is the region between a chord and its associated arc.
        </p>
    </insight>

